eft\"|[[Slovak language|Slovak]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Interlanguage link multi|Mari\u00e1n Slov\u00e1k|sk|3=Mari\u00e1n Slov\u00e1k}}\n|align=\"left\"|\"D\u00e1m signal\"\n|align=\"left\"|\"I'll give a signal\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |[[Slovene language|Slovene]]\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |Mitja \u0160edlbauer\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |\"Bli\u017ea se\"\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |\"It's getting closer\"\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Castilian Spanish|Spanish <small>(Europe)</small>]]\n| align=\"left\" |Jordi Doncos\n| align=\"left\" |\"Preparaos\"\n| align=\"left\" |\"Ready\"\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Spanish language in the Americas|Spanish <small>(Latin America)</small>]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{Interlanguage link multi|Carlos Petrel|es|3=Carlos Petrel}} \n| align=\"left\" |\"Listos ya\"\n| align=\"left\" |\"Ready now\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Rikard Wolff]]\n|align=\"left\"|\"Var beredd\"\n|align=\"left\"|\"Be ready\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |[[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |[[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Thai language|Thai]]\n|align=\"left\"|\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e31\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c \u0e2a\u0e38\u0e27\u0e23\u0e23\u0e13\u0e28\u0e23 (Prat Suwannason)\n|\"\u0e08\u0e07\u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e40\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e30\" (\"?\")\n|{{unknown}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n|align=\"left\"|{{Interlanguage link multi|\u015eahin \u00c7elik|tr|3=\u015eahin \u00c7elik}}\n|align=\"left\"|\"Haz\u0131r olun\"\n|align=\"left\"|\"Be prepared\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0422\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0443\u043a (Volodymyr Tereshchuk)\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |\"\u0427\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\" (\"Chas nastav\")\n| style=\"background:Azure\" |\"Time has come\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Zulu language|Zulu]]\n|Victor Masondo\n|\"Zilungeselele\"\n|{{unknown}}\n|}\n\n===Deleted reprise===\n[[File:Be Prepared reprise.ogg|thumb|right|Though an important plot, the reprise was deleted from the film as it was considered too dark.]]\n\nDuring early production of the film, there was a reprise created of the song, taking place after Scar has assumed power over the Pride Lands. He is given the idea by Zazu to find a mate. So he tries seducing [[Nala (The Lion King)|Nala]], who refuses his advances, and is therefore banished by Scar. He then unleashes the hyenas upon the Pride Lands as his \"executive staff\". The reprise was ultimately removed from the film and the concept was later recycled in \"[[The Madness of King Scar]]\" was included in the Broadway musical version of the film.<ref>{{cite video|title=Scar Wants Nala as His Queen|author=Allers, Roger|authorlink=Roger Allers|location=The Lion King: Diamond Edition |type = Blu-ray |year=2011 |publisher=Walt Disney Home Entertainment}}</ref>\n\n==''The Lion King 1\u00bd''==\nIn [[DisneyToon Studios|DisneyToon]]'s 2004 direct-to-video film ''[[The Lion King 1\u00bd]]'', the music from the beginning of the song is briefly heard as [[Timon and Pumbaa]] tour Scar's lair as a possible new home, commenting on how it is quiet, secluded and with no uninvited visitors. The shadows of the goose-stepping hyena army are then seen marching in front of them, though they haven't started singing yet. Timon and Pumbaa stare at them for a few seconds, and remark that the hyenas \"ain't the traveling company of [[Riverdance]].\" They then riverdance out of the scene.\n\n==''The Lion King'' (2019)==\nOn February 3, 2019, Skyler Shuler of The DisInsider reported that \"Be Prepared\" would be one of the songs featured in the [[The Lion King (2019 film)|2019 remake of ''The Lion King'']], directed by [[Jon Favreau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Be-Prepared-Will-Be-Featured-in-THE-LION-KING-Live-Action-Film-20190203|title='Be Prepared' Will Be Featured in THE LION KING Live Action Film|first=Stephanie|last=Wild|work=BroadwayWorld|date=February 3, 2019|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/04/29/the-lion-king-scar/|title=The Lion King\u2019s Chiwetel Ejiofor on the diabolical psychology of Scar|first=Marc|last=Snetiker|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=April 29, 2019|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> On June 24, 2019, the remake was confirmed to feature a reworked version of the song.<ref name=\"Soundtrack\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-lion-king-soundtrack-details-new-song|title=\u2018The Lion King\u2019 Soundtrack Details Revealed; Includes New Elton John Song|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|work=[[Collider]]|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==''The Lion King'' Broadway musical==\nAs in the original soundtrack recording, Scar begins the song with a brief soliloquy. The song is similar to its film counterpart in most respects, including the goose stepping hyenas, but there is a dance number performed by the hyena ensemble halfway through.  Scar later sings a brief [[reprise]] while declaring himself king at Mufasa's funeral in which he introduces the hyenas as his direct and privileged minions (the aforementioned deleted reprise from the film).  However, the Broadway reprise was not featured in the soundtrack, and is instead replaced with a sinister chord at the end of the song \"Rafiki Mourns\". In other soundtracks from different productions, the song is not represented at all.\n\n==''Festival of The Lion King''==\nIn [[Walt Disney World]]'s [[Disney's Animal Kingdom|Animal Kingdom]]'s ''[[Festival of the Lion King]]'', Kiume sings the song while the theater takes on a darker tone with the male dancers carrying spears and shields, while the female dancers dance with streamers. After Kiume sings the first verse, the solo hyena performer does a tribal dance with a fire torch. In the finale, when the snippet of \"Be Prepared\" is sung, the hyena comes back out but dances with blades.\n==Reception==\n===Original Version===\nThe song has garnered positive reaction and review. Becky Fuller from [[Screen Rant]] gave the song's original version a positive review. He describes the song as \"camp, fun, and just scary enough to make younger viewers feel a little on edge\" and perfectly summed up Scar's character. He praised Jeremy Irons' performance, citing his deep, dulcet tones is perfect for the song. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/lion-king-2019-be-prepared-villain-song-bad/|title=The Lion King 2019 Gets All the Songs Right (Except Be Prepared)|first=Becky|last=Fuller|work=[[Screen Rant]]|date=July 21, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n[[Glen Weldon]] from [[NPR]] also praised the song as indelible and iconic for its pure expression of Scar's character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/17/742204352/lion-king-2019-be-prepared-villain-anthem-jeremy-irons-chiwetel-ejiofor|title=The Lion King Had the Perfect Villain Song, This Time Be Prepared for Less|first=Glen|last=Weldon|work=[[NPR]]|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref> Hannah-Rose Yee from Stylist cited Be Prepared as one of the best songs in the film for mixing humor and tragedy in the lyrics that builds up the character's deluded aspiration and twisted desire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stylist.co.uk/life/lion-king-live-action-be-prepared-cut-elton-john-beyonce/271463|title=Lion King fans, beware: the live action movie has cut the film's best song|first=Hannah-Rose|last=Yee|work=Stylist|date=June 14, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Remake===\nThe remake song received a mixed to negative reaction. Fuller criticised the 2019 remake of the song, commenting \"it feels like Scar is merely relaying some information to audiences that could have been delivered in a speech\" and felt it would have been better if the song is not included at all.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/lion-king-2019-be-prepared-villain-song-bad/|title=The Lion King 2019 Gets All the Songs Right (Except Be Prepared)|first=Becky|last=Fuller|work=[[Screen Rant]]|date=July 21, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\nSimilarly, Weldon criticized the song for cutting most of the verses, commenting the song sounds more like \"if the Boy Scouts imposed martial law\" and make Scar's character like \"a mere feckless politician attempting to sway a potential ally.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/17/742204352/lion-king-2019-be-prepared-villain-anthem-jeremy-irons-chiwetel-ejiofor|title=The Lion King Had the Perfect Villain Song, This Time Be Prepared for Less|first=Glen|last=Weldon|work=[[NPR]]|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|XkU23m6yX04}}\n\n{{The Lion King}}\n\n[[Category:1994 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Tim Rice]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Elton John]]\n[[Category:Songs from The Lion King]]\n[[Category:Songs about royalty]]\n[[Category:Songs about betrayal]]\n[[Category:Songs about revenge]]\n[[Category:Jim Cummings songs]]\n", "name_user": "70.119.19.250", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThe Lion King (2019))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Be_Prepared_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Piano Tiles 2", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Piano Tiles}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Piano Tiles 2\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| image = Piano Tiles 2 logo.png\n| caption = Piano Tiles 2 logo\n| developer = [[Cheetah Mobile]]\n| publisher = Cheetah Mobile\n| series = Piano Tiles\n| engine = \n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| released = August 19, 2015\n| genre = Arcade\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Piano Tiles 2''''' is a music arcade game, created by Hu Wen Zeng. It is published by the Entertainment department of [[Cheetah Mobile]]. The game's aim is to tap the black tiles without making any mistakes. It was published in August 2015 as the sequel of ''[[Piano Tiles]]''. It has been removed from Google's Play Store in early March 2020 due to dangerous adware and malware files found in Cheetah Mobile's applications.There is also a Umod version of the game (Only for Android) with other songs which is made by Southey, Beeps , ade, tastyBlackTiles, ADRIAN66M and most recently VarxenCore9.\n\n[[File:Piano tiles 2 Level Little Star.jpg|thumb|First level of a game in Piano Tiles 2, [[Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star|Little Star]].]]\n\n== Reception ==\nAccording to App Annie, the game was the #1 downloaded app in 151 countries. In 2016, the game was awarded Best Game of 2015 by Google Play, reaching new heights in its global achievements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.appannie.com/insights/top-trending-apps/piano-tiles-2-now-trending-global-rise/|title=Now Trending: Piano Tiles 2's Rise on the Global Stage|publisher=}}</ref> Pocketgamer complimented ''Piano Tiles 2'' in its article that \"bringing the piano-playing sensation to the next level.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/iPhone/Piano%20Tiles%202/news.asp?c=67319|title=Check out what PewDiePie thinks of Piano Tiles 2|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHowever, some have criticised the game for only having one game mode, rather than multiple ones.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/piano-tiles-2-review-1992952|title=Piano Tiles 2 Review: Melodious|work=Lifewire|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref> There has also been criticism over the new lives system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/piano-tiles-2-dont-tap-the-white-tile-2|title=Piano Tiles 2 (Don't Tap The White Tile 2)|website=Metacritic|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\nSongs in ''Piano Tiles 2'' mainly consist of classical music, and folk music. Examples include [[Pachelbel's Canon]] (classical, level 3). Songs can be unlocked by leveling up and/or by purchase. Some songs includes Jingle Bells, notable songs include those by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin]] such as his Nocturne Op. 9 No. 2 and Waltz in A minor, [[Franz Schubert]]'s [[Six Moments Musicaux (Schubert)|Six Moments Musicaux]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s [[Eine Kleine Nachtmusik]]. There are seasonal folk songs and festive songs. It also includes the modern hits like \"[[Faded (Alan Walker song)|Faded]]\", \"[[Despacito]]\" by [[Luis Fonsi]] and \"[[Alone (Alan Walker song)|Alone]]\" by Alan Walker, and a December 2018 update of \"[[The Spectre (song)|The Spectre]]\". Modded songs created by user such as \"[[Shape of You]]\" by [[Ed Sheeran]] also spread on YouTube.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WB5gmLmsUMg </ref>. In 2019, \"[[Swear It Again]]\" by [[Westlife]] are rumored to be released.\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://cheetahgames.cmcm.com/PianoTiles2 Piano Tiles 2] at [https://cheetahgames.cmcm.com Cheetah Games]\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Piano Tiles}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Piano Tiles 2\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| image = Piano Tiles 2 logo.png\n| caption = Piano Tiles 2 logo\n| developer = [[Cheetah Mobile]]\n| publisher = Cheetah Mobile\n| series = Piano Tiles\n| engine = \n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| released = August 19, 2015\n| genre = Arcade\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Piano Tiles 2''''' is a music arcade game, created by Hu Wen Zeng. It is published by the Entertainment department of [[Cheetah Mobile]]. The game's aim is to tap the black tiles without making any mistakes. It was published in August 2015 as the sequel of ''[[Piano Tiles]]''. It has been removed from Google's Play Store in early March 2020 due to dangerous adware and malware files found in Cheetah Mobile's applications.\n\n[[File:Piano tiles 2 Level Little Star.jpg|thumb|First level of a game in Piano Tiles 2, [[Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star|Little Star]].]]\n\n== Reception ==\nAccording to App Annie, the game was the #1 downloaded app in 151 countries. In 2016, the game was awarded Best Game of 2015 by Google Play, reaching new heights in its global achievements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.appannie.com/insights/top-trending-apps/piano-tiles-2-now-trending-global-rise/|title=Now Trending: Piano Tiles 2's Rise on the Global Stage|publisher=}}</ref> Pocketgamer complimented ''Piano Tiles 2'' in its article that \"bringing the piano-playing sensation to the next level.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/iPhone/Piano%20Tiles%202/news.asp?c=67319|title=Check out what PewDiePie thinks of Piano Tiles 2|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHowever, some have criticised the game for only having one game mode, rather than multiple ones.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/piano-tiles-2-review-1992952|title=Piano Tiles 2 Review: Melodious|work=Lifewire|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref> There has also been criticism over the new lives system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/piano-tiles-2-dont-tap-the-white-tile-2|title=Piano Tiles 2 (Don't Tap The White Tile 2)|website=Metacritic|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\nSongs in ''Piano Tiles 2'' mainly consist of classical music, and folk music. Examples include [[Pachelbel's Canon]] (classical, level 3). Songs can be unlocked by leveling up and/or by purchase. Some songs includes Jingle Bells, notable songs include those by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin]] such as his Nocturne Op. 9 No. 2 and Waltz in A minor, [[Franz Schubert]]'s [[Six Moments Musicaux (Schubert)|Six Moments Musicaux]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s [[Eine Kleine Nachtmusik]]. There are seasonal folk songs and festive songs. It also includes the modern hits like \"[[Faded (Alan Walker song)|Faded]]\", \"[[Despacito]]\" by [[Luis Fonsi]] and \"[[Alone (Alan Walker song)|Alone]]\" by Alan Walker, and a December 2018 update of \"[[The Spectre (song)|The Spectre]]\". Modded songs created by user such as \"[[Shape of You]]\" by [[Ed Sheeran]] also spread on YouTube.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WB5gmLmsUMg </ref>. In 2019, \"[[Swear It Again]]\" by [[Westlife]] are rumored to be released.\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://cheetahgames.cmcm.com/PianoTiles2 Piano Tiles 2] at [https://cheetahgames.cmcm.com Cheetah Games]\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n", "name_user": "Djiscool27", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added Umod pt2 to pt2 wiki)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piano_Tiles_2"}
{"title_page": "Touch ID", "text_new": "[[File:IPhone 6s - Touch ID front view-93104.jpg|thumb|Touch ID module of an [[iPhone 6S]]]]\n[[File:Touch ID logo.png|thumb|200px|Logo used by Apple to indicate Touch ID technology.]]\n'''Touch ID''' is an [[electronic fingerprint recognition]] feature, designed and released by Apple inc, that allows users to unlock [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] devices, make purchases in the various Apple digital media stores (the [[iTunes Store]], the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]], and the [[Ibookstore|Apple Books Store]]), and authenticate [[Apple Pay]] online or in apps. It can also be used to lock and unlock password-protected [[Notes (Apple)|notes]] on iPhone and iPad.  \n\nIt has been part of all [[iPhone]]s since 2013's [[iPhone 5S]] up until 2020\u2019s [[iPhone SE (2020)|iPhone SE (2nd generation)]]. Touch ID has been used on all [[iPad|iPads]] since 2014's [[iPad Air 2]], with the exception of the third and subsequent generations of the [[iPad Pro]], where it has been discontinued in favor of Face ID. In 2015, Apple introduced a faster second-generation Touch ID in the [[iPhone 6S]]; a year later in 2016, it made its laptop debut in the [[MacBook Pro]] integrated on the right side of the [[Touch Bar]]. In MacBooks, each user account can have up to three fingerprints, and a total of five fingerprints across the system<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://support.apple.com/en-ae/HT204587 |title = About Touch ID advanced security technology}}</ref>.\nIn 2017, Apple released the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus with Touch ID, alongside the [[iPhone X]] that instead incorporated [[Face ID]].\n\nIn 2020, Apple announced the return of the classic Touch ID sensor, this time on the iPhone SE (2nd generation), which has a similar design to the iPhone 8. This is the first iPhone to feature Touch ID since the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus, both released in 2017.\n\nFingerprint information is stored locally in a [[IOS#Secure_Enclave|secure enclave]] on the [[Apple A7]] and later chips, not in the [[Cloud computing|cloud]], a design choice intended to make it impossible for users to externally access the fingerprint information.\n\n==History==\n[[File:iPhone 5S home button.png|thumb|right|The [[iPhone 5S]] ''(pictured)'' was the first model with a Touch ID sensor integrated with its home button.]]\nIn 2012, Apple acquired [[AuthenTec]], a company focused on fingerprint reading and identification management software, for $356 million.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57602245-37/fingerprint-sensor-touch-id-unlocks-new-iphones|title=iPhone 5S comes with Touch ID fingerprint scanner|last=Rosenblatt|first=Seth|date=September 10, 2013|publisher=[[CNET]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The acquisition led commentators to expect a fingerprint reading feature.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\" /><ref name=\"TC announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/10/apples-touch-id-a-500ppi-fingerprint-sensor-built-into-iphone-5s-home-button|title=Apple's Touch ID Is A 500ppi Fingerprint Sensor Built Into The iPhone 5S Home Button|last=Valazco|first=Chris|date=September 11, 2013|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Following leaks and speculation in early September,<ref name=\"NWE touch id leak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowhereelse.fr/bouton-home-iphone-5s-lecteur-empreintes-digitales-87919|title=iPhone 5S : Une photo du bouton Home avec lecteur d'empreintes digitales ?!|date=September 3, 2013|publisher=NowhereElse|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NWE leak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowhereelse.fr/iphone-5s-lecteur-empreintes-digitales-confirme-88283|title=iPhone 5S : Le lecteur d'empreintes digitales confirm\u00e9 ?!|date=September 10, 2013|publisher=NowhereElse|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> the iPhone 5S was unveiled on September 10, 2013, and was the first phone on a major US carrier to feature the technology.<ref name=\"The Verge announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/10/4715372/confirmed-apple-iphone-5s-will-include-touch-id-fingerprint-scanner|title=Apple's new iPhone will read your fingerprint|publisher=[[The Verge]]|first=Casey|last=Newton|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Apple's [[Vice president|Vice President]] of Marketing, [[Phil Schiller]], announced the feature at Apple's iPhone media event and spent several minutes (the major portion of the conference) discussing the feature.\n\nWells Fargo analyst Maynard Um predicted on September 4, 2013, that a fingerprint sensor in the [[iPhone 5S]] would help [[mobile commerce]] and boost adoption in the corporate environment.<ref name=\"Apple Insider predicted\">{{cite web|url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/09/04/fingerprint-sensor-in-apples-iphone-5s-predicted-to-boost-mobile-commerce-enterprise-adoption|title=Fingerprint sensor in Apple's 'iPhone 5S' predicted to boost mobile commerce, enterprise adoption|publisher=[[AppleInsider]]|first=Neil|last=Hughes|date=September 4, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> \"As consumers increasingly rely on mobile devices to transact and store personal data, a reliable device-side authentication solution may become a necessity,\" Um said.<ref name=\"Apple Insider predicted\"/>\n\nWith the unveiling of the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus at a keynote event on September 9, 2014, Touch ID was expanded from being used to unlock the device and authenticating App Store purchases to also authenticating Apple Pay. The [[iPhone 6s|iPhone 6S]] incorporates a second-generation Touch ID sensor that is up to twice as fast as the first-generation sensor found in the 5S, 6, and SE (1st generation) phones. As of April 2020, the iPhone 6S, 6S Plus, 7, 7 Plus, 8, 8 Plus, SE (2nd generation) (2020), 2016 and 2017 MacBook Pro, iPad Pro 10.5 and 12.9 (second generation), and 2018 [[MacBook Air]] are the Apple devices which use the second generation sensor. The new Touch ID unlocks almost instantly and posed an issue as it unlocks too fast to read notifications on the lock screen. This is remedied with the [[iOS 10]] update in which a user must press the home button to have the home screen appear, however this can be changed in the iOS settings to where users can just rest their finger on the sensor to unlock the user's device and go directly to the home screen, similar to previous versions of iOS. Solely placing a finger on the sensor will only unlock the iPhone unless said setting is enabled, and no notifications are currently being displayed on the lock screen.\n\n==Generations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Generation\n! Model\n|-\n| 1\n|\n* [[iPhone 5S]]\n* [[iPhone SE (1st generation)]]\n* [[iPhone 6]] \n* [[iPhone 6 Plus]]\n* [[iPad Mini 3|iPad mini 3]]\n* [[iPad (2017)]]\n* [[iPad (2018)]]\n* [[iPad (2019)]]\n\n|-\n| 2\n| \n* [[iPhone 6S]] \n* [[iPhone 6S Plus]]\n* [[iPhone 7]]\n* [[iPhone 7 Plus]]\n* [[iPhone 8]]\n* [[iPhone 8 Plus]]\n* [[iPhone SE (2nd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9-inch (1st generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 9.7-inch]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9-inch (2nd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 10.5-inch]]\n* [[iPad Air 2]]\n* [[iPad Air 3|iPad Air (3rd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Mini 4|iPad mini 4]]\n* [[iPad Mini 5|iPad mini (5th generation)]]\n* [[MacBook Air|MacBook Air (2018)]]\n* [[MacBook Pro]]\n\n|}\n\n==Hardware==\n[[Image:TouchID components.png|thumb|right|Components of Touch ID.]]\n\nTouch ID is built into the home button, which is built of [[laser]]-cut<ref name=\"Apple press release\">{{cite web|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130910-909214.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913010513/http://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130910-909214.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 13, 2013|title=Apple Announces iPhone 5S - The Most Forward-Thinking Smartphone in the World|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> [[sapphire crystal]], and does not scratch easily (scratching would prevent Touch ID from working).<ref name=\"Apple Insider iPhone 5S announcement\">{{cite web|url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/09/10/apple-announces-iphone-5s-with-64-bit-a7-cpu-new-gold-option|title=Apple announces iPhone 5S: Touch ID fingerprint security, 64-bit A7 CPU, new gold option coming Sept. 20|publisher=[[AppleInsider]]|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> It features a stainless steel detection ring to detect the user's finger without pressing it. There is no longer a rounded square icon in the home button, nor is it concave.\n\nThe sensor uses [[Capacitive sensing|capacitive touch]] to detect the user's fingerprint.<ref name=\"Apple Insider iPhone 5S announcement\"/> The sensor has a thickness of 170&nbsp;[[\u00b5m]], with 500 [[pixel density|pixels per inch resolution]]. The user's finger can be oriented in any direction and it will still be read.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\"/> Apple says it can read sub-epidermal skin layers,<ref name=\"Engadget announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/iphone-5s-fingerprint-sensor|title=iPhone 5s fingerprint sensor called Touch ID, recognizes your thumb on the Home button: here's how it works and what it does|publisher=[[Engadget]]|first=Ben|last=Gilbert|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> and it will be easy to set up and will improve with every use.<ref name=\"Apple press release\"/> The sensor passes a small current through one's finger to create a \"fingerprint map\" of the user's dermis. Up to 5 fingerprint maps can be stored in the Secure Enclave.\n\n==Security and privacy==\n{{Multiple image\n | image1 = OneDrive, Touch ID.png\n | width1 = 150\n | alt1   = Screenshot of the passcode screen of OneDrive on iOS 11, with the prompt for Touch ID unlock displayed\n | image2 = Microsoft Outlook, Touch ID.png\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2   = Screenshot of the loading screen of Microsoft Oulook on iOS 11, with the prompt for Touch ID unlock displayed\n | footer = Touch ID prompts on opening screens of the [[OneDrive]] (left) and [[Microsoft Outlook|Outlook]] (right) applications in [[iOS 11]].\n}}\nTouch ID can be bypassed using passcodes set up by the user.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT204060 |title = Use a passcode with your iPhone, iPad, or iPod touch}}</ref>\n\nFingerprint data is stored on the secure enclave inside the [[Apple A7]], [[Apple A8|A8]], [[Apple A8X|A8X]], [[Apple A9|A9]], [[Apple A9X|A9X]], [[Apple A10 Fusion|A10]], [[Apple A10X|A10X]], [[Apple A11|A11]], [[Apple A12|A12]], [[Apple A13|A13]] processors of an iOS device, and not on Apple servers, nor on iCloud. From the Efficient Texture Comparison patent<ref name=\"Efficient Texture Comparison patent\">{{cite web|url=http://appft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&d=PG01&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsrchnum.html&r=1&f=G&l=50&s1=%2220130308838%22.PGNR.&OS=DN/20130308838&RS=DN/20130308838|title=Efficient Texture Comparison|publisher=[[US Patent & Trademark Office]]|work=Digital|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref> covering Apple's Touch ID technology: <blockquote>In order to overcome potential security drawbacks, Apple's invention includes a process of collapsing the full maps into a sort of [[checksum]], hash function, or [[histogram]]. For example, each encrypted ridge map template can have some lower resolution pattern computed and associated with the ridge map. One exemplary pattern could be a histogram of, e.g., the most common angles (e.g., a 2 dimensional (2D) array of common angles). The exemplary pattern could include in each slot an average value over a respective vector of the map. The exemplary pattern could include in each slot a sum of the values over a respective vector of the map. The exemplary pattern could include the smallest or largest value within a respective vector of the map or could be a difference between a largest and a smallest value within the respective vector of the map. Numerous other exemplary embodiments are also possible, and any other exemplary pattern calculation can be used, where the exemplary pattern includes enough associated information to narrow the candidate list, while omitting enough associated information that the unsecured pattern cannot or cannot easily be reverse engineered into a matching texture.</blockquote>If the user's phone has been rebooted, has not been unlocked for 48 hours, has its SIM card removed or if Emergency SOS was activated, only the passcode a user has created, not their fingerprint, can be used to unlock the device, or during other specific use cases.<ref name=\"wsj code entry\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2013/09/11/apple-new-iphone-not-storing-fingerprints-doesnt-like-sweat|title=Apple: New iPhone Not Storing Fingerprints, Doesn't Like Sweat|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|work=Digital|date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/business/docs/iOS_Security_Guide.pdf|title=iOS Security Guide|last=|first=|date=March 2017|website=[[Apple Inc.]]|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, the German [[Chaos Computer Club]] announced that it had bypassed Apple's Touch ID security. A spokesman for the group stated: \"We hope that this finally puts to rest the illusions people have about fingerprint biometrics. It is plain pity to use something that you can't change and that you leave everywhere every day as a security token.\"<ref name=\"ccc touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ccc.de/en/updates/2013/ccc-breaks-apple-touchid|title=Chaos Computer Club breaks Apple Touch ID|publisher=[[Chaos Computer Club]]|first=Frank|last=Rieger|date=September 21, 2013|accessdate=September 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57604067-37/hackers-claim-to-have-defeated-apples-touch-id-print-sensor|title=Hackers claim to have defeated Apple's Touch ID print sensor|work=[[CNet]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive Inc.]]|first=Stephen|last=Musil|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>  Similar results have been achieved by using [[Polyvinyl acetate|PVA Glue]] to take a cast of the finger.<ref name=\"lookout touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.lookout.com/blog/2013/09/23/why-i-hacked-apples-touchid-and-still-think-it-is-awesome|title=Why I Hacked Apple's TouchID, And Still Think It Is Awesome|publisher=Lookout|first=Marc|last=Rogers|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324173742/https://blog.lookout.com/blog/2013/09/23/why-i-hacked-apples-touchid-and-still-think-it-is-awesome/|archivedate=2017-03-24}}</ref> Others have also used Chaos Computer Club's method, but concluded that it is not an easy process in either time or effort, given that the user has to use a high resolution photocopy of a complete fingerprint, special chemicals and expensive equipment, and because the spoofing process takes some time to achieve.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://blog.lookout.com/iphone-6-touchid-hack |title = Why I hacked TouchID (Again) and still think it's awesome}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n<!-- fingerprint recognition adoption -->\nIn a 2013 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine opinion piece, Kevin Roose argued that consumers are generally not interested in fingerprint recognition, preferring to use passcodes instead. Traditionally, he wrote, only businesspeople used biometric recognition, although they believe Touch ID may help bring fingerprint recognition to the masses. Roose stated the feature will also allow application developers to experiment, should Apple open up access to Touch ID later on (which they have done), but that those wary of surveillance agencies such as the US [[National Security Agency]] may still choose not to use Touch ID.<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/09/will-apples-touch-id-make-fingerprints-happen.html|title=Will the New iPhone's 'Touch ID' Feature Finally Make Fingerprint Scanning Happen?|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=September 10, 2013|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<!-- hardware problems -->\nRoose also noted that fingerprint technology still has some issues, such as the potential to be hacked, or of the device's not recognizing the fingerprint (for example, when the finger has been injured).<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\"/>\n\n<!-- security / theft -->\nAdrian Kingsley-Hughes, writing for [[ZDNet]], said Touch ID could be useful in [[bring your own device]] situations. He said the biometric protection adds another layer of security, removing the ability of people to look over others' shoulders and read their passcode/password. He added that Touch ID would prevent children from racking up thousands of dollars in unwanted purchases when using iPhones owned by adults. He observed that Touch ID was Apple's response to the large number of iPhone crimes, and that the new feature would deter would-be iPhone thieves.\n\nMoreover, he notes that the feature is one of the few that distinguish the iPhone 5S from the 5C.<ref name=\"ZDNet BYOD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/apples-touch-id-is-a-big-win-for-byod-security-7000020499|title=iPhone 5S with Touch ID is a big win for BYOD security|website=[[ZDNet]]|first=Adrian|last=Kingsley-Hughes|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Roose also stated the feature is intended to deter theft.<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\"/> However, Brent Kennedy, a vulnerability analyst at the [[United States Computer Emergency Readiness Team]], expressed concern that Touch ID could be hacked and suggested that people not rely on it right away.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/09/10/apples-new-iphones-touch-id-makes-fingerprint-scans-easy-but-dont-ditch-your-passcode-yet|title=Apple's New iPhone 'Touch ID' Makes Fingerprint Scans Easy, But Don't Ditch Passcodes Yet|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Andy|last=Greenberg|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> ''Forbes'' noted a history of fingerprints being spoofed in the past, and cautioned that the fingerprints on a stolen iPhone might be used to gain unauthorized access. However, the article did say that biometrics technology had improved since tests on spoofing fingerprint readers had been conducted.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\"/>\n\nKingsley-Hughes suggested the Touch ID as a form of [[two-factor authentication]], combining something one ''knows'' (the password) with \"something you are\" (the fingerprint).<ref name=\"ZDNet BYOD\"/> ''Forbes'' said that, if two-factor authentication is available, it will be an overall improvement for security.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\"/>\n\n<!-- government agency concerns -->\n''Forbes'' columnist Andy Greenberg said the fact that fingerprint data was stored on the local device and not in a centralized database was a win for security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/josephsteinberg/2013/09/13/your-new-iphone-can-put-your-identity-at-risk/|title=Your New iPhone Can Put Your Identity At Risk|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Joseph|last=Steinberg|date=September 13, 2013|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Face ID]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://support.apple.com/HT204587|About Touch ID security on iPhone and iPad}} \u2013 official site\n* {{official website|https://support.apple.com/HT201371|Use Touch ID on iPhone and iPad}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{iOS}}\n\n[[Category:Authentication methods]]\n[[Category:Fingerprints]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:IPhone 6s - Touch ID front view-93104.jpg|thumb|Touch ID module of an [[iPhone 6S]]]]\n[[File:Touch ID logo.png|thumb|200px|Logo used by Apple to indicate Touch ID technology.]]\n'''Touch ID''' is an [[electronic fingerprint recognition]] feature, designed and released by Apple inc, that allows users to unlock [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] devices, make purchases in the various Apple digital media stores (the [[iTunes Store]], the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]], and the [[Ibookstore|Apple Books Store]]), and authenticate [[Apple Pay]] online or in apps. It can also be used to lock and unlock password-protected [[Notes (Apple)|notes]] on iPhone and iPad.  \n\nIt has been part of all [[iPhone]]s since 2013's [[iPhone 5S]] up until 2020\u2019s [[iPhone SE (2020)|iPhone SE (2nd generation)]]. Touch ID has been used on all [[iPad|iPads]] since 2014's [[iPad Air 2]], with the exception of the third and subsequent generations of the [[iPad Pro]], where it has been discontinued in favor of Face ID. In 2015, Apple introduced a faster second-generation Touch ID in the [[iPhone 6S]]; a year later in 2016, it made its laptop debut in the [[MacBook Pro]] integrated on the right side of the [[Touch Bar]]. In MacBooks, each user account can have up to three fingerprints, and a total of five fingerprints across the system<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://support.apple.com/en-ae/HT204587 |title = About Touch ID advanced security technology}}</ref>.\nIn 2017, Apple released the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus with Touch ID, alongside the [[iPhone X]] that instead incorporated [[Face ID]].\n\nIn 2020, Apple announced the return of the classic Touch ID sensor, this time on the iPhone SE (2nd generation), which has a similar design to the iPhone 8. This is the first iPhone to feature Touch ID since the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus, both released in 2017.\n\nFingerprint information is stored locally in a [[IOS#Secure_Enclave|secure enclave]] on the [[Apple A7]] and later chips, not in the [[Cloud computing|cloud]], a design choice intended to make it impossible for users to externally access the fingerprint information.\n\n==History==\n[[File:iPhone 5S home button.png|thumb|right|The [[iPhone 5S]] ''(pictured)'' was the first model with a Touch ID sensor integrated with its home button.]]\nIn 2012, Apple acquired [[AuthenTec]], a company focused on fingerprint reading and identification management software, for $356 million.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57602245-37/fingerprint-sensor-touch-id-unlocks-new-iphones|title=iPhone 5S comes with Touch ID fingerprint scanner|last=Rosenblatt|first=Seth|date=September 10, 2013|publisher=[[CNET]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The acquisition led commentators to expect a fingerprint reading feature.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\" /><ref name=\"TC announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/10/apples-touch-id-a-500ppi-fingerprint-sensor-built-into-iphone-5s-home-button|title=Apple's Touch ID Is A 500ppi Fingerprint Sensor Built Into The iPhone 5S Home Button|last=Valazco|first=Chris|date=September 11, 2013|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Following leaks and speculation in early September,<ref name=\"NWE touch id leak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowhereelse.fr/bouton-home-iphone-5s-lecteur-empreintes-digitales-87919|title=iPhone 5S : Une photo du bouton Home avec lecteur d'empreintes digitales ?!|date=September 3, 2013|publisher=NowhereElse|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NWE leak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowhereelse.fr/iphone-5s-lecteur-empreintes-digitales-confirme-88283|title=iPhone 5S : Le lecteur d'empreintes digitales confirm\u00e9 ?!|date=September 10, 2013|publisher=NowhereElse|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> the iPhone 5S was unveiled on September 10, 2013, and was the first phone on a major US carrier to feature the technology.<ref name=\"The Verge announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/10/4715372/confirmed-apple-iphone-5s-will-include-touch-id-fingerprint-scanner|title=Apple's new iPhone will read your fingerprint|publisher=[[The Verge]]|first=Casey|last=Newton|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Apple's [[Vice president|Vice President]] of Marketing, [[Phil Schiller]], announced the feature at Apple's iPhone media event and spent several minutes (the major portion of the conference) discussing the feature.\n\nWells Fargo analyst Maynard Um predicted on September 4, 2013, that a fingerprint sensor in the [[iPhone 5S]] would help [[mobile commerce]] and boost adoption in the corporate environment.<ref name=\"Apple Insider predicted\">{{cite web|url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/09/04/fingerprint-sensor-in-apples-iphone-5s-predicted-to-boost-mobile-commerce-enterprise-adoption|title=Fingerprint sensor in Apple's 'iPhone 5S' predicted to boost mobile commerce, enterprise adoption|publisher=[[AppleInsider]]|first=Neil|last=Hughes|date=September 4, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> \"As consumers increasingly rely on mobile devices to transact and store personal data, a reliable device-side authentication solution may become a necessity,\" Um said.<ref name=\"Apple Insider predicted\"/>\n\nWith the unveiling of the iPhone 6 and 6 Plus at a keynote event on September 9, 2014, Touch ID was expanded from being used to unlock the device and authenticating App Store purchases to also authenticating Apple Pay. The [[iPhone 6s|iPhone 6S]] incorporates a second-generation Touch ID sensor that is up to twice as fast as the first-generation sensor found in the 5S, 6, and SE (1st generation) phones. As of April 2020, the iPhone 6S, 6S Plus, 7, 7 Plus, 8, 8 Plus, SE (2nd generation) (2020), 2016 and 2017 MacBook Pro, iPad Pro 10.5 and 12.9 (second generation), and 2018 [[MacBook Air]] are the Apple devices which use the second generation sensor. The new Touch ID unlocks almost instantly and posed an issue as it unlocks too fast to read notifications on the lock screen. This is remedied with the [[iOS 10]] update in which a user must press the home button to have the home screen appear, however this can be changed in the iOS settings to where users can just rest their finger on the sensor to unlock the user's device and go directly to the home screen, similar to previous versions of iOS. Solely placing a finger on the sensor will only unlock the iPhone unless said setting is enabled, and no notifications are currently being displayed on the lock screen.\n\n==Generations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Generation\n! Model\n|-\n| 1\n|\n* [[iPhone 5S]]\n* [[iPhone SE (1st generation)]]\n* [[iPhone 6]] \n* [[iPhone 6 Plus]]\n* [[iPad Mini 3|iPad mini 3]]\n* [[iPad (2017)]]\n* [[iPad (2018)]]\n* [[iPad (2019)]]\n\n|-\n| 2\n| \n* [[iPhone 6S]] \n* [[iPhone 6S Plus]]\n* [[iPhone 7]]\n* [[iPhone 7 Plus]]\n* [[iPhone 8]]\n* [[iPhone 8 Plus]]\n* [[iPhone SE (2nd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9-inch (1st generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 9.7-inch]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9-inch (2nd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 10.5-inch]]\n* [[iPad Air 2]]\n* [[iPad Air 3|iPad Air (3rd generation)]]\n* [[iPad Mini 4|iPad mini 4]]\n* [[iPad Mini 5|iPad mini (5th generation)]]\n* [[MacBook Air|MacBook Air (2018)]]\n* [[MacBook Pro]]\n\n|}\n\n==Hardware==\n[[Image:TouchID components.png|thumb|right|Components of Touch ID.]]\n\nTouch ID is built into the home button, which is built of [[laser]]-cut<ref name=\"Apple press release\">{{cite web|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130910-909214.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913010513/http://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130910-909214.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 13, 2013|title=Apple Announces iPhone 5S - The Most Forward-Thinking Smartphone in the World|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> [[sapphire crystal]], and does not scratch easily (scratching would prevent Touch ID from working).<ref name=\"Apple Insider iPhone 5S announcement\">{{cite web|url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/09/10/apple-announces-iphone-5s-with-64-bit-a7-cpu-new-gold-option|title=Apple announces iPhone 5S: Touch ID fingerprint security, 64-bit A7 CPU, new gold option coming Sept. 20|publisher=[[AppleInsider]]|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> It features a stainless steel detection ring to detect the user's finger without pressing it. There is no longer a rounded square icon in the home button, nor is it concave.\n\nThe sensor uses [[Capacitive sensing|capacitive touch]] to detect the user's fingerprint.<ref name=\"Apple Insider iPhone 5S announcement\"/> The sensor has a thickness of 170&nbsp;[[\u00b5m]], with 500 [[pixel density|pixels per inch resolution]]. The user's finger can be oriented in any direction and it will still be read.<ref name=\"CNET announcement\"/> Apple says it can read sub-epidermal skin layers,<ref name=\"Engadget announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/iphone-5s-fingerprint-sensor|title=iPhone 5s fingerprint sensor called Touch ID, recognizes your thumb on the Home button: here's how it works and what it does|publisher=[[Engadget]]|first=Ben|last=Gilbert|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> and it will be easy to set up and will improve with every use.<ref name=\"Apple press release\"/> The sensor passes a small current through one's finger to create a \"fingerprint map\" of the user's dermis. Up to 5 fingerprint maps can be stored in the Secure Enclave.\n\n==Security and privacy==\n{{Multiple image\n | image1 = OneDrive, Touch ID.png\n | width1 = 150\n | alt1   = Screenshot of the passcode screen of OneDrive on iOS 11, with the prompt for Touch ID unlock displayed\n | image2 = Microsoft Outlook, Touch ID.png\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2   = Screenshot of the loading screen of Microsoft Oulook on iOS 11, with the prompt for Touch ID unlock displayed\n | footer = Touch ID prompts on opening screens of the [[OneDrive]] (left) and [[Microsoft Outlook|Outlook]] (right) applications in [[iOS 11]].\n}}\nTouch ID can be bypassed using passcodes set up by the user.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT204060 |title = Use a passcode with your iPhone, iPad, or iPod touch}}</ref>\n\nFingerprint data is stored on the secure enclave inside the [[Apple A7]], [[Apple A8|A8]], [[Apple A8X|A8X]], [[Apple A9|A9]], [[Apple A9X|A9X]], [[Apple A10 Fusion|A10]], [[Apple A10X|A10X]], [[Apple A11|A11]], [[Apple A12|A12]], [[Apple A13|A13]] processors of an iOS device, and not on Apple servers, nor on iCloud. From the Efficient Texture Comparison patent<ref name=\"Efficient Texture Comparison patent\">{{cite web|url=http://appft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&d=PG01&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsrchnum.html&r=1&f=G&l=50&s1=%2220130308838%22.PGNR.&OS=DN/20130308838&RS=DN/20130308838|title=Efficient Texture Comparison|publisher=[[US Patent & Trademark Office]]|work=Digital|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref> covering Apple's Touch ID technology: <blockquote>In order to overcome potential security drawbacks, Apple's invention includes a process of collapsing the full maps into a sort of [[checksum]], hash function, or [[histogram]]. For example, each encrypted ridge map template can have some lower resolution pattern computed and associated with the ridge map. One exemplary pattern could be a histogram of, e.g., the most common angles (e.g., a 2 dimensional (2D) array of common angles). The exemplary pattern could include in each slot an average value over a respective vector of the map. The exemplary pattern could include in each slot a sum of the values over a respective vector of the map. The exemplary pattern could include the smallest or largest value within a respective vector of the map or could be a difference between a largest and a smallest value within the respective vector of the map. Numerous other exemplary embodiments are also possible, and any other exemplary pattern calculation can be used, where the exemplary pattern includes enough associated information to narrow the candidate list, while omitting enough associated information that the unsecured pattern cannot or cannot easily be reverse engineered into a matching texture.</blockquote>If the user's phone has been rebooted, has not been unlocked for 48 hours, has its SIM card removed or if Emergency SOS was activated, only the passcode a user has created, not their fingerprint, can be used to unlock the device, or during other specific use cases.<ref name=\"wsj code entry\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2013/09/11/apple-new-iphone-not-storing-fingerprints-doesnt-like-sweat|title=Apple: New iPhone Not Storing Fingerprints, Doesn't Like Sweat|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|work=Digital|date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/business/docs/iOS_Security_Guide.pdf|title=iOS Security Guide|last=|first=|date=March 2017|website=[[Apple Inc.]]|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, the German [[Chaos Computer Club]] announced that it had bypassed Apple's Touch ID security. A spokesman for the group stated: \"We hope that this finally puts to rest the illusions people have about fingerprint biometrics. It is plain pity to use something that you can't change and that you leave everywhere every day as a security token.\"<ref name=\"ccc touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ccc.de/en/updates/2013/ccc-breaks-apple-touchid|title=Chaos Computer Club breaks Apple Touch ID|publisher=[[Chaos Computer Club]]|first=Frank|last=Rieger|date=September 21, 2013|accessdate=September 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57604067-37/hackers-claim-to-have-defeated-apples-touch-id-print-sensor|title=Hackers claim to have defeated Apple's Touch ID print sensor|work=[[CNet]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive Inc.]]|first=Stephen|last=Musil|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>  Similar results have been achieved by using [[Polyvinyl acetate|PVA Glue]] to take a cast of the finger.<ref name=\"lookout touch ID bypass\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.lookout.com/blog/2013/09/23/why-i-hacked-apples-touchid-and-still-think-it-is-awesome|title=Why I Hacked Apple's TouchID, And Still Think It Is Awesome|publisher=Lookout|first=Marc|last=Rogers|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324173742/https://blog.lookout.com/blog/2013/09/23/why-i-hacked-apples-touchid-and-still-think-it-is-awesome/|archivedate=2017-03-24}}</ref> Others have also used Chaos Computer Club's method, but concluded that it is not an easy process in either time or effort, given that the user has to use a high resolution photocopy of a complete fingerprint, special chemicals and expensive equipment, and because the spoofing process takes some time to achieve.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://blog.lookout.com/iphone-6-touchid-hack |title = Why I hacked TouchID (Again) and still think it's awesome}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n<!-- fingerprint recognition adoption -->\nIn a 2013 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine opinion piece, Kevin Roose argued that consumers are generally not interested in fingerprint recognition, preferring to use passcodes instead. Traditionally, he wrote, only businesspeople used biometric recognition, although they believe Touch ID may help bring fingerprint recognition to the masses. Roose stated the feature will also allow application developers to experiment, should Apple open up access to Touch ID later on (which they have done), but that those wary of surveillance agencies such as the US [[National Security Agency]] may still choose not to use Touch ID.<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/09/will-apples-touch-id-make-fingerprints-happen.html|title=Will the New iPhone's 'Touch ID' Feature Finally Make Fingerprint Scanning Happen?|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=September 10, 2013|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<!-- hardware problems --> Roose also noted that fingerprint technology still has some issues, such as the potential to be hacked, or of the device's not recognizing the fingerprint (for example, when the finger has been injured).<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\"/>\n\n<!-- security / theft -->\nAdrian Kingsley-Hughes, writing for [[ZDNet]], said Touch ID could be useful in [[bring your own device]] situations. He said the biometric protection adds another layer of security, removing the ability of people to look over others' shoulders and read their passcode/password. He added that Touch ID would prevent children from racking up thousands of dollars in unwanted purchases when using iPhones owned by adults. He observed that Touch ID was Apple's response to the large number of iPhone crimes, and that the new feature would deter would-be iPhone thieves.\n\nMoreover, he notes that the feature is one of the few that distinguish the iPhone 5S from the 5C.<ref name=\"ZDNet BYOD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/apples-touch-id-is-a-big-win-for-byod-security-7000020499|title=iPhone 5S with Touch ID is a big win for BYOD security|website=[[ZDNet]]|first=Adrian|last=Kingsley-Hughes|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Roose also stated the feature is intended to deter theft.<ref name=\"NY Mag happen\"/> However, Brent Kennedy, a vulnerability analyst at the [[United States Computer Emergency Readiness Team]], expressed concern that Touch ID could be hacked and suggested that people not rely on it right away.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/09/10/apples-new-iphones-touch-id-makes-fingerprint-scans-easy-but-dont-ditch-your-passcode-yet|title=Apple's New iPhone 'Touch ID' Makes Fingerprint Scans Easy, But Don't Ditch Passcodes Yet|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Andy|last=Greenberg|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> ''Forbes'' noted a history of fingerprints being spoofed in the past, and cautioned that the fingerprints on a stolen iPhone might be used to gain unauthorized access. However, the article did say that biometrics technology had improved since tests on spoofing fingerprint readers had been conducted.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\"/>\n\nKingsley-Hughes suggested the Touch ID as a form of [[two-factor authentication]], combining something one ''knows'' (the password) with \"something you are\" (the fingerprint).<ref name=\"ZDNet BYOD\"/> ''Forbes'' said that, if two-factor authentication is available, it will be an overall improvement for security.<ref name=\"forbes security 1\"/>\n\n<!-- government agency concerns -->\n''Forbes'' columnist Andy Greenberg said the fact that fingerprint data was stored on the local device and not in a centralized database was a win for security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/josephsteinberg/2013/09/13/your-new-iphone-can-put-your-identity-at-risk/|title=Your New iPhone Can Put Your Identity At Risk|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Joseph|last=Steinberg|date=September 13, 2013|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Face ID]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://support.apple.com/HT204587|About Touch ID security on iPhone and iPad}} \u2013 official site\n* {{official website|https://support.apple.com/HT201371|Use Touch ID on iPhone and iPad}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{iOS}}\n\n[[Category:Authentication methods]]\n[[Category:Fingerprints]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n", "name_user": "Ghostofakina", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Touch_ID"}
{"title_page": "Chatime", "text_new": "{{short description|Taiwanese global franchise teahouse chain based in Taiwan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Chatime\n| native_name = \u65e5\u51fa\u8336\u592a \n| native_name_lang = zh\n| logo = [[File:Chatime Logo.png|250px|Chatime logo]]\n| type =\n| traded_as = \n| foundation = [[Zhubei]], [[Hsinchu County]], Taiwan (2005) opened 2006<ref name=phil-star/>\n| founder = \n| location_city = Zhubei, Hsinchu County\n| location_country = Taiwan\n| locations = 2500 in 38 countries <small>(December 2018)</small>\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = Henry Wang Yao-Hui<br><small>(Chairperson, Founder)</small><ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|title=La Kaffa International Co Ltd|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/2732:TT|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> \n| industry = [[Beverages]]\n| genre = [[Bubble tea]]\n| products = {{flatlist|[[Bubble tea]] {{\u2022}}Tea {{\u2022}}[[Flavored tea]]}}\n| services = Tea\n| revenue = US$20 million (2011)<ref name=phil-star/><ref name=\"PDI-Manila\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income =  \n| assets =  \n| equity =  \n| num_employees = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|chatime.com.tw/zh}}           \n             {{URL|chatime.com.tw/en}} \n}}\n\n'''Chatime''' ({{zh|c=\u65e5\u51fa\u8336\u592a}}) is a [[Taiwan]]ese global [[Franchising|franchise]] [[teahouse|teahouse chain]] based in [[Zhubei]]. Chatime is the largest teahouse franchise in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrmonline.com.au/underpayment/chatime-final-straw-australias-franchise-sector/|title=Will Chatime be the final straw for Australia\u2019s franchise sector?|date=2019-04-30|website=HRM online|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Its expansion and growth model is through [[franchising]].<ref name=\"taipeitimes-expansion\"/> It operates 2500+ outlets in 38 countries. In 2006, it opened its first store outside of Taiwan in California, United States and it has since expanded to China, Malaysia, Canada, Bangladesh, Indonesia, Philippines, Cambodia, Thailand, United States, Australia, New Zealand, India, United Arab Emirates, Japan and South Korea, among others now.<ref name=taipeitimes-expansion>{{cite news|last=Su|first=Amy|title=Food, beverage firms plan expansion|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2013/04/08/2003559046|accessdate=26 July 2013|newspaper=Taipei Times|date=8 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=IRA-korea>{{cite news|title=Chatime enters Korea|url=http://www.insideretail.asia/InsideRetailAsia/InsideRetailAsianews/Chatime-enters-Korea-6437.aspx|accessdate=26 July 2013|newspaper=Inside Retail Asia|date=18 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025081726/http://www.insideretail.asia/InsideRetailAsia/InsideRetailAsianews/Chatime-enters-Korea-6437.aspx|archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIts parent company, {{interlanguage link|La Kaffa International Co Ltd|zh|\u516d\u89d2\u570b\u969b\u96c6\u5718}}, debuted on the Emerging Stock Market ({{lang|zh-hant|\u8208\u6ac3\u5e02\u5834}}) in December 2012 at NT$168 per share. It is the only [[Public company|publicly listed]] [[bubble tea]] company in Taiwan.<ref name=edge-tea/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chatime drinks.jpg|thumb|left|Chatime tea.]]\nHenry Wang Yao-Hui founded Chatime in 2005 in [[Hsinchu]], [[Taiwan]], under the parent company, La Kaffa Coffee.<ref name=PDI-Manila>{{cite news|last=Baga-Reyes|first=Reyes|title=How Taipei\u2019s Chatime came to Manila|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/45061/how-taipei%E2%80%99s-chatime-came-to-manila|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\nThe company opened its first outlet outside of Taiwan in California in 2006,<ref name=IRA-korea/> followed by Australia in 2009,<ref name=\"Neat Eats\">{{cite web|title=Bubble tea|url=http://www.neateats.com.au/2012/09/bubble-tea/|publisher=Neat Eats Food news|accessdate=9 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231144755/http://www.neateats.com.au/2012/09/bubble-tea/#|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  where it currently has over 70 stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatime Franchising|url=https://chatime.com.au/franchising/|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref>  This was followed by Malaysia<ref name=\"Star People\">{{cite news|title=Chatime boss finds his cup of tea|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/Lifestyle/People/2013/11/11/Chatime-boss-finds-his-cup-of-tea.aspx|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=11 November 2013}}</ref> in 2010.<ref name=LK100>{{cite web|title=Chatime Malaysia Celebrates 100 Outlets|url=http://www.lakaffagroup.com/webe/html/news/show.php?num=190&kind=27&type=1&page=1|publisher=La Kaffa|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231201715/http://www.lakaffagroup.com/webe/html/news/show.php?num=190&kind=27&type=1&page=1|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> Its Malaysian operations currently account for just under 50% of its global revenue.<ref name=\"Star People\"/>\n\nIn 2012, the brand opened its first store in India, a traditional tea drinking country, in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=WCT>{{cite news|title=Chatime opens Taiwanese bubble tea store in New Delhi|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20120803000056&cid=1206|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Want China Times|date=3 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231225212/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20120803000056&cid=1206|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter its two stores in New York, its third store in the United States opened at [[Mall of America]] in March 2012.<ref name=moa>{{cite web|title=Chatime to open at Mall of America|url=http://www.minneapolis.org/article/chatime-%E2%80%93-serving-world-renowned-bubble-tea-%E2%80%93-open-mall-america|publisher=Minneapolis.org|accessdate=10 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231200057/http://www.minneapolis.org/article/chatime-%E2%80%93-serving-world-renowned-bubble-tea-%E2%80%93-open-mall-america|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> The Chatime store in London is located on [[Old Compton Street]].<ref name=ad-lib>{{cite web|title=Chatime\u2019 makes its European d\u00e9but in London|url=http://adlibtraveller.com/blog/united-kingdom-uk/limelight-chatime-makes-its-european-debut-in-london/|publisher=Ad-lib Traveller|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the Philippines, it planned to open 50 stores by 2014,<ref name=phil-star>{{cite news|last=Jamora-Garceau|first=Therese|title=Lifestyle report from Taiwan: What time is it? It's Chatime|url=http://www.philstar.com/food-and-leisure/795699/lifestyle-report-taiwan-what-time-it-its-chatime|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Phil Star|date=12 April 2012}}</ref> while in Malaysia, it opened its 100th store in 2013, with plans to open up to 250 stores within a three to five-year period.<ref name=star-100>{{cite news|last=Chan|first=Jade|title=Chatime unveils expansion plan at opening of its 100th store|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Community/2013/07/26/Sustainable-concept-for-hotel-Chatime-unveils-expansion-plan-at-opening-of-its-100th-store.aspx|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2018, the brand has 16 locations throughout [[Vancouver]], BC and 2 locations in [[Halifax, NS]], Canada, as well as one in [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]], ON. [[Sydney, NS]] also has one as of January 2020.\n\nAs of 2020, Chatime has ten stores in [[Dhaka]] and one store in [[Chittagong]] in [[Bangladesh]].\n\n[[File:Chatime AEON Bukit Tinggi, Klang.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chatime outlet in [[\u00c6on Group|\u00c6on]], [[Bandar Bukit Tinggi]], [[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Malaysia]]]]\nChatime's parent company, La Kaffa International Co. Ltd., debuted on [[Gre Tai Securities Market|Taiwan's Emerging Stock Market]] (\u8208\u6ac3\u5e02\u5834) in December 2012 at NT$168 per share<ref name=greTai>{{cite web|title=Announcement - La Kaffa|url=http://www.gretai.org.tw/en/bulletin/market_announcement/announce_detail.php?doc_id=81&sid=1|publisher=GreTai Securities Market|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> under the stock code 2732.<ref name=\"taipeitimes-expansion\"/> It is the only publicly listed bubble tea company in Taiwan.<ref name=edge-tea>{{cite news|title=mad about tea - How to sell bubble tea profitably|url=http://www.theedgemalaysia.com/personal-finance/196175-mad-about-tea-how-to-sell-bubble-tea-profitably.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Edge|date=15 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513070315/http://www.theedgemalaysia.com/personal-finance/196175-mad-about-tea-how-to-sell-bubble-tea-profitably.html|archivedate=13 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nThe brand's best-selling drink is its Chatime \"pearl\" milk tea.<ref name=\"PDI-Manila\"/> The brand has a variety of drinks under categories such as milk tea, fresh tea, fruit tea, \"oriental pop tea\", \"QQ\" jelly (Not available in Australia), \"mousse\", juices, smoothies and coffee.<ref name=chatimeproducts>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://www.chatimecafe.com/products.html|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125121656/http://www.chatimecafe.com/products.html|archivedate=25 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=dink-products>{{cite web|title=Drinks|url=http://www.chatime.com.my/varietea/drinks/all|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231181546/http://www.chatime.com.my/varietea/drinks/all|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> Its products are available with less sugar.<ref name=phil-star/>\n\nTypically, Chatime products come with a variety of toppings such as \"[[bubble tea|pearls]]\", while \"QQ\" jelly is a mixture of \"pearls\" and [[nata de coco]].<ref name=phil-star/>\n\nSome products are only available in certain countries. For example, in Malaysia, Chatime introduced three flavours in collaboration with [[Horlicks]] from [[GlaxoSmithKline]].<ref name=horlicks>{{cite news|last=Sri Priya|first=Sheila|title=Tea with Horlicks for Chatime|url=http://www.nst.com.my/streets/central/tea-with-horlicks-for-chatime-1.206912|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=25 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101004529/http://www.nst.com.my/streets/central/tea-with-horlicks-for-chatime-1.206912#|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nAs of 2018, Chatime is present in 39 countries and territories.<ref name=locations>{{cite web|title=Locations|url=http://www.ichatime.com.tw/webe/html/stores/index2.php?kind=33|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=23 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725072505/http://www.ichatime.com.tw/webe/html/stores/index2.php?kind=33#|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n<!-- sorted by short column -->\n!America\n!Europe\n!Middle East\n!Africa\n!Oceania\n!Asia<!-- sorted by long column -->\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| and an extra spicy man\n*Canada\n*United States\n*Mexico\n*Colombia\n|\n*United Kingdom\n*France\n*Germany\n*Czech Republic\n*Iceland\n|\n*United Arab Emirates\n*Oman\n*Kuwait\n*Qatar\n*Lebanon\n|\n* Mauritius\n|\n* Australia\n* Guam\n* New Zealand\n* Fiji\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n* Bangladesh\n* Brunei\n* Cambodia\n* China (Mainland)\n* Hong Kong (China)\n* India\n* Indonesia\n* Japan\n* Macau (China)\n* Malaysia\n* Maldives\n* Myanmar\n* Pakistan\n* Philippines\n* Singapore\n* South Korea\n* Taiwan\n* Thailand\n* Vietnam\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:Chatime Map.svg|center|650px]]\n|}\n\n==Collaborations==\n[[File:Chatime AirAsia launch.jpg|thumbnail|left|Chatime was the first [[bubble tea]] brand to be made available in-flight in a collaboration with [[AirAsia]]]]\n[[File:Chatime and WeChat.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chatime became the first beverage company in Malaysia to host an official account on [[WeChat]]. On the far left and right are WeChat ambassadors [[Lisa Surihani]] and [[Shaheizy Sam]].<ref name=tech-quest>{{cite web|last=Yu|first=Steve|title=WeChat celebrates partnership with Chatime with 1 Million Cups of Chatime for Redemption|url=http://mytechquest.com/tech-news/wechatime-1-million-cups-celebration/|publisher=My Techj Quest|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2012, [[AirAsia]] announced that it would offer Chatime on its flights and claimed that is would be the \"world's first and only in-flight bubble tea\". The airline said that two speciality bubble tea drinks, Roasted Milk Tea with Red Bean and Mango Green Tea with Rainbow Jelly, were available on flights operated by Malaysian AirAsia with the airline code AK to 48 destinations, which include India, Hong Kong, Thailand and the Philippines.<ref name=dailyexpress-airasia>{{cite news|title=AirAsia upbeat on its F&B growth|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=82028|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Daily Express|date=6 July 2012}}</ref> The collaboration was organised by Chatime Malaysia's CEO, Bryan Loo.<ref name=dailyexpress-airasia/>\n\nChatime became the first beverage company in Malaysia to host an official account on [[WeChat]]. To mark the collaboration, Chatime gave away 1 million cups of drinks worth over  [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]6 million/[[United states dollar|US$]]2 million through digital coupons made available via the WeChat platform.<ref name=wechat-bp>{{cite news|title=WeChat and Chatime offer 1 million cups of Chatime |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/10/21/wechat-and-chatime-offer1-million-cups-of-chatime/|accessdate=30 December 2013|newspaper=Borneo Post|date=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nOther collaborations include partnerships with [[McDonald's]],  [[Horlicks]] from [[GlaxoSmithKline]],<ref name=mm-horlicks>{{cite news|title=The \"Why\" Behind the Chatime-Horlicks Alliance|url=http://marketingmagazine.com.my/index.php/categories/breaking-news/8812-the-qwhyq-behind-the-chatime-horlicks-alliance|accessdate=31 December 2013|newspaper=Marketing Magazine|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101023815/http://marketingmagazine.com.my/index.php/categories/breaking-news/8812-the-qwhyq-behind-the-chatime-horlicks-alliance|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  and biscuit brand Julie's.<ref name=bt-julies>{{cite news|title=Julie\u2019s teams up with Chatime|url=http://www.btimes.com.my/Current_News/BTIMES/articles/20131122005843/Article/|accessdate=31 December 2013|newspaper=Business Times|date=22 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101002340/http://www.btimes.com.my/Current_News/BTIMES/articles/20131122005843/Article/|archivedate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Brand ambassadors==\n[[File:Chatime outlet.jpg|thumbnail|right|A Chatime outlet in a shopping mall]]\n[[File:ChatimeOxford.jpg|thumb|right|A Chatime outlet]]\nChatime announced in 2012 that award-winning Taiwan actress [[Ariel Lin]] would serve as its [[brand ambassador]].<ref name=chatime-ariellin>{{cite web|title=Ariel Lin as the Official Brand Ambassador for Chatime|url=http://www.tea-time.com.tw/webe/html/news/show.php?num=6&kind=3&page=1|publisher=Chatime Press Release|accessdate=10 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231191247/http://www.tea-time.com.tw/webe/html/news/show.php?num=6&kind=3&page=1|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, the brand announced that [[Crystal Lee]] had become the lifestyle tea provider's first \"Chatime Friend\". The announcement was made soon after Lee became the youngest actress ever to have won the award for Best Actress at the 16th [[Shanghai International Film Festival]].<ref name=star-crystal>{{cite news|title=Award-winning child actress debuts in brand's programme|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/Business/SME/2013/07/02/Crystal-forges-special-friendship-Awardwinning-child-actress-debuts-in-brands-programme.aspx|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Counterfeit==\nIn South Korea, Chatime said it would take legal action against a store which sold similar products and was recruiting potential franchises.<ref name=wca-korea>{{cite news |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20121018000142&cid=1102 |title=Taiwanese bubble tea chain opens first outlet in South Korea |newspaper=[[WantChinaTimes]] |date=18 October 2012 |accessdate=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231223229/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20121018000142&cid=1102 |archivedate=31 December 2013 }}</ref> Additionally, in Malaysia, they will seek an injunction against  newly launched [[Tealive]] for operating and selling similar products and the possibility of using the same trade practices as its predecessor, Chatime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/03/16/chatime-malaysia-sues-tealive |title=Chatime Malaysia sues Tealive |date=16 March 2018 |website=The Sun Daily |publisher=Sun Media |accessdate=27 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316111512/http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/03/16/chatime-malaysia-sues-tealive |archivedate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Legal & regulatory matters==\nIn Malaysia, the master franchisee agreement was terminated on 5 January 2017 by La Kaffa International due to contractual dispute with its country master franchisee, Loob Holding. This legal dispute attracted the attention of local media and is currently in arbitration in Singapore. La Kaffa held a press conference in [[Kuala Lumpur]] announcing it would be taking over the Malaysian Chatime business operations and development with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/malaysia-s-chatime-outlets-to-be-replaced-with-local-brand-after-7577712 |title=Malaysia's Chatime outlets to be replaced with local brand after franchise dispute |last=Naidu |first=Sumisha |date=25 January 2017 |website=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |publisher=[[Mediacorp]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> This however appears to be largely incorrect with Loob Holding rebranding 161 out of 165 Chatime outlets to Tealive brand on 17 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2017/02/17/loob-holding-rebrands-chatime-as-tealive/ |title=Loob Holding rebrands Chatime as Tealive |date=17 February 2017 |website=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star Online]] |publisher=Star Media Group |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1317151/chatime-is-tealive-from-now-on-says-loob |title=Chatime is Tealive from now on, says Loob |date=17 February 2017 |website=[[Malay Mail]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Due to Loob Holding's alleged use of unapproved ingredients (which were later found out to be collaborations with other brands for localization purposes),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://says.com/my/news/la-kaffa-accuses-chatime-outlets-in-malaysia-of-using-unapproved-ingredients |title=La Kaffa Accuses Chatime Outlets In Malaysia Of Using \"Unapproved Ingredients\" |last=Balakrishnan |first=Nandini |date=3 February 2017 |website=[[Says Sdn Bhd|Says]] |publisher=[[Rev Asia]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> questionable practices, and a blatant breach of the terms of contract, La Kaffa International director Chen Zhao sought an injunction against the former master franchisee from operating a similar (bubble tea) business in Malaysia. On 29 May 2017, the High Court dismissed the injunction bid by La Kaffa International, against Loob Holding Sdn Bhd, from carrying a similar business as Chatime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/05/29/court-dismisses-chatimes-bid-for-injunction-against-ex-franchise-holder/ |title=Court dismisses Chatime's bid for injunction against ex-franchise holder |last=Ho |first=Kit Yen |date=29 May 2017 |website=[[Free Malaysia Today]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Judicial Commissioner Wong Kian Kheong, in his oral judgement, ruled that the injunction would cause great risk of injustice to Loob Holding and its business and also associates. The court also found that the franchise termination by La Kaffa was done in bad faith. While both companies have taken their dispute to the Singapore International Arbitration Centre, La Kaffa reportedly tries to persuade Loob Holding to settle this matter outside court.\n\nChatime Australia is alleged  to have underpaid 152 employees of 10 company-owned outlets across in Sydney and Melbourne a total of about $169,000.<ref name=\"9Newsunder\">{{cite news |last1=AAP |title=Chatime bubble tea chain allegedly underpaid staff |url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/chatime-australia-bubble-tea-chain-underpaying-staff/aa0c7f0c-1b68-4503-b26d-314852dbfdca |accessdate=28 December 2019 |agency=9News |date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bubble tea]]\n*[[Tea house]]\n*[[Tea culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chatime.com.tw/zh Official Taiwanese Website]\n*[http://www.chatime.com.tw/en Official English Website]\n\n[[Category:Tea houses]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese brands]]\n[[Category:Tea brands]]\n[[Category:Bubble tea brands]]\n[[Category:Tea companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Tea estates]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hsinchu]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Taiwan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Taiwanese global franchise teahouse chain based in Taiwan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Chatime\n| native_name = \u65e5\u51fa\u8336\u592a \n| native_name_lang = zh\n| logo = [[File:Chatime Logo.png|250px|Chatime logo]]\n| type =\n| traded_as = \n| foundation = [[Zhubei]], [[Hsinchu County]], Taiwan (2005) opened 2006<ref name=phil-star/>\n| founder = \n| location_city = Zhubei, Hsinchu County\n| location_country = Taiwan\n| locations = 2500 in 38 countries <small>(December 2018)</small>\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = Henry Wang Yao-Hui<br><small>(Chairperson, Founder)</small><ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|title=La Kaffa International Co Ltd|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/2732:TT|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> \n| industry = [[Beverages]]\n| genre = [[Bubble tea]]\n| products = {{flatlist|[[Bubble tea]] {{\u2022}}Tea {{\u2022}}[[Flavored tea]]}}\n| services = Tea\n| revenue = US$20 million (2011)<ref name=phil-star/><ref name=\"PDI-Manila\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income =  \n| assets =  \n| equity =  \n| num_employees = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|chatime.com.tw/zh}}           \n             {{URL|chatime.com.tw/en}} \n}}\n\n'''Chatime''' ({{zh|c=\u65e5\u51fa\u8336\u592a}}) is a [[Taiwan]]ese global [[Franchising|franchise]] [[teahouse|teahouse chain]] based in [[Zhubei]]. Chatime is the largest teahouse franchise in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrmonline.com.au/underpayment/chatime-final-straw-australias-franchise-sector/|title=Will Chatime be the final straw for Australia\u2019s franchise sector?|date=2019-04-30|website=HRM online|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Its expansion and growth model is through [[franchising]].<ref name=\"taipeitimes-expansion\"/> It operates 2500+ outlets in 38 countries. In 2006, it opened its first store outside of Taiwan in California, United States and it has since expanded to China, Malaysia, Canada, Bangladesh, Indonesia, Philippines, Cambodia, Thailand, United States, Australia, New Zealand, India, United Arab Emirates, Japan and South Korea, among others now.<ref name=taipeitimes-expansion>{{cite news|last=Su|first=Amy|title=Food, beverage firms plan expansion|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2013/04/08/2003559046|accessdate=26 July 2013|newspaper=Taipei Times|date=8 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=IRA-korea>{{cite news|title=Chatime enters Korea|url=http://www.insideretail.asia/InsideRetailAsia/InsideRetailAsianews/Chatime-enters-Korea-6437.aspx|accessdate=26 July 2013|newspaper=Inside Retail Asia|date=18 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025081726/http://www.insideretail.asia/InsideRetailAsia/InsideRetailAsianews/Chatime-enters-Korea-6437.aspx|archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIts parent company, {{interlanguage link|La Kaffa International Co Ltd|zh|\u516d\u89d2\u570b\u969b\u96c6\u5718}}, debuted on the Emerging Stock Market ({{lang|zh-hant|\u8208\u6ac3\u5e02\u5834}}) in December 2012 at NT$168 per share. It is the only [[Public company|publicly listed]] [[bubble tea]] company in Taiwan.<ref name=edge-tea/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chatime drinks.jpg|thumb|left|Chatime tea.]]\nHenry Wang Yao-Hui founded Chatime in 2005 in [[Hsinchu]], [[Taiwan]], under the parent company, La Kaffa Coffee.<ref name=PDI-Manila>{{cite news|last=Baga-Reyes|first=Reyes|title=How Taipei\u2019s Chatime came to Manila|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/45061/how-taipei%E2%80%99s-chatime-came-to-manila|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\nThe company opened its first outlet outside of Taiwan in California in 2006,<ref name=IRA-korea/> followed by Australia in 2009,<ref name=\"Neat Eats\">{{cite web|title=Bubble tea|url=http://www.neateats.com.au/2012/09/bubble-tea/|publisher=Neat Eats Food news|accessdate=9 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231144755/http://www.neateats.com.au/2012/09/bubble-tea/#|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  where it currently has over 70 stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatime Franchising|url=https://chatime.com.au/franchising/|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref>  This was followed by Malaysia<ref name=\"Star People\">{{cite news|title=Chatime boss finds his cup of tea|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/Lifestyle/People/2013/11/11/Chatime-boss-finds-his-cup-of-tea.aspx|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=11 November 2013}}</ref> in 2010.<ref name=LK100>{{cite web|title=Chatime Malaysia Celebrates 100 Outlets|url=http://www.lakaffagroup.com/webe/html/news/show.php?num=190&kind=27&type=1&page=1|publisher=La Kaffa|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231201715/http://www.lakaffagroup.com/webe/html/news/show.php?num=190&kind=27&type=1&page=1|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> Its Malaysian operations currently account for just under 50% of its global revenue.<ref name=\"Star People\"/>\n\nIn 2012, the brand opened its first store in India, a traditional tea drinking country, in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=WCT>{{cite news|title=Chatime opens Taiwanese bubble tea store in New Delhi|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20120803000056&cid=1206|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=Want China Times|date=3 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231225212/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20120803000056&cid=1206|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter its two stores in New York, its third store in the United States opened at [[Mall of America]] in March 2012.<ref name=moa>{{cite web|title=Chatime to open at Mall of America|url=http://www.minneapolis.org/article/chatime-%E2%80%93-serving-world-renowned-bubble-tea-%E2%80%93-open-mall-america|publisher=Minneapolis.org|accessdate=10 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231200057/http://www.minneapolis.org/article/chatime-%E2%80%93-serving-world-renowned-bubble-tea-%E2%80%93-open-mall-america|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> The Chatime store in London is located on [[Old Compton Street]].<ref name=ad-lib>{{cite web|title=Chatime\u2019 makes its European d\u00e9but in London|url=http://adlibtraveller.com/blog/united-kingdom-uk/limelight-chatime-makes-its-european-debut-in-london/|publisher=Ad-lib Traveller|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the Philippines, it planned to open 50 stores by 2014,<ref name=phil-star>{{cite news|last=Jamora-Garceau|first=Therese|title=Lifestyle report from Taiwan: What time is it? It's Chatime|url=http://www.philstar.com/food-and-leisure/795699/lifestyle-report-taiwan-what-time-it-its-chatime|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Phil Star|date=12 April 2012}}</ref> while in Malaysia, it opened its 100th store in 2013, with plans to open up to 250 stores within a three to five-year period.<ref name=star-100>{{cite news|last=Chan|first=Jade|title=Chatime unveils expansion plan at opening of its 100th store|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Community/2013/07/26/Sustainable-concept-for-hotel-Chatime-unveils-expansion-plan-at-opening-of-its-100th-store.aspx|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2018, the brand has 16 locations throughout [[Vancouver]], BC and 2 locations in [[Halifax, NS]], Canada, as well as one in [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]], ON. [[Sydney, NS]] also has one as of January 2020.\n\nAs of 2020, Chatime has ten stores in [[Dhaka]] and one store in [[Chittagong]] in [[Bangladesh]].\n\n[[File:Chatime AEON Bukit Tinggi, Klang.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chatime outlet in [[\u00c6on Group|\u00c6on]], [[Bandar Bukit Tinggi]], [[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Malaysia]]]]\nChatime's parent company, La Kaffa International Co. Ltd., debuted on [[Gre Tai Securities Market|Taiwan's Emerging Stock Market]] (\u8208\u6ac3\u5e02\u5834) in December 2012 at NT$168 per share<ref name=greTai>{{cite web|title=Announcement - La Kaffa|url=http://www.gretai.org.tw/en/bulletin/market_announcement/announce_detail.php?doc_id=81&sid=1|publisher=GreTai Securities Market|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> under the stock code 2732.<ref name=\"taipeitimes-expansion\"/> It is the only publicly listed bubble tea company in Taiwan.<ref name=edge-tea>{{cite news|title=mad about tea - How to sell bubble tea profitably|url=http://www.theedgemalaysia.com/personal-finance/196175-mad-about-tea-how-to-sell-bubble-tea-profitably.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Edge|date=15 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513070315/http://www.theedgemalaysia.com/personal-finance/196175-mad-about-tea-how-to-sell-bubble-tea-profitably.html|archivedate=13 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nThe brand's best-selling drink is its Chatime \"pearl\" milk tea.<ref name=\"PDI-Manila\"/> The brand has a variety of drinks under categories such as milk tea, fresh tea, fruit tea, \"oriental pop tea\", \"QQ\" jelly (Not available in Australia), \"mousse\", juices, smoothies and coffee.<ref name=chatimeproducts>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://www.chatimecafe.com/products.html|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125121656/http://www.chatimecafe.com/products.html|archivedate=25 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=dink-products>{{cite web|title=Drinks|url=http://www.chatime.com.my/varietea/drinks/all|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=9 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231181546/http://www.chatime.com.my/varietea/drinks/all|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref> Its products are available with less sugar.<ref name=phil-star/>\n\nTypically, Chatime products come with a variety of toppings such as \"[[bubble tea|pearls]]\", while \"QQ\" jelly is a mixture of \"pearls\" and [[nata de coco]].<ref name=phil-star/>\n\nSome products are only available in certain countries. For example, in Malaysia, Chatime introduced three flavours in collaboration with [[Horlicks]] from [[GlaxoSmithKline]].<ref name=horlicks>{{cite news|last=Sri Priya|first=Sheila|title=Tea with Horlicks for Chatime|url=http://www.nst.com.my/streets/central/tea-with-horlicks-for-chatime-1.206912|accessdate=9 December 2013|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=25 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101004529/http://www.nst.com.my/streets/central/tea-with-horlicks-for-chatime-1.206912#|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nAs of 2018, Chatime is present in 39 countries and territories.<ref name=locations>{{cite web|title=Locations|url=http://www.ichatime.com.tw/webe/html/stores/index2.php?kind=33|publisher=Chatime|accessdate=23 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725072505/http://www.ichatime.com.tw/webe/html/stores/index2.php?kind=33#|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n<!-- sorted by short column -->\n!America\n!Europe\n!Middle East\n!Africa\n!Oceania\n!Asia<!-- sorted by long column -->\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*Canada\n*United States\n*Mexico\n*Colombia\n|\n*United Kingdom\n*France\n*Germany\n*Czech Republic\n*Iceland\n|\n*United Arab Emirates\n*Oman\n*Kuwait\n*Qatar\n*Lebanon\n|\n* Mauritius\n|\n* Australia\n* Guam\n* New Zealand\n* Fiji\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n* Bangladesh\n* Brunei\n* Cambodia\n* China (Mainland)\n* Hong Kong (China)\n* India\n* Indonesia\n* Japan\n* Macau (China)\n* Malaysia\n* Maldives\n* Myanmar\n* Pakistan\n* Philippines\n* Singapore\n* South Korea\n* Taiwan\n* Thailand\n* Vietnam\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:Chatime Map.svg|center|650px]]\n|}\n\n==Collaborations==\n[[File:Chatime AirAsia launch.jpg|thumbnail|left|Chatime was the first [[bubble tea]] brand to be made available in-flight in a collaboration with [[AirAsia]]]]\n[[File:Chatime and WeChat.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chatime became the first beverage company in Malaysia to host an official account on [[WeChat]]. On the far left and right are WeChat ambassadors [[Lisa Surihani]] and [[Shaheizy Sam]].<ref name=tech-quest>{{cite web|last=Yu|first=Steve|title=WeChat celebrates partnership with Chatime with 1 Million Cups of Chatime for Redemption|url=http://mytechquest.com/tech-news/wechatime-1-million-cups-celebration/|publisher=My Techj Quest|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2012, [[AirAsia]] announced that it would offer Chatime on its flights and claimed that is would be the \"world's first and only in-flight bubble tea\". The airline said that two speciality bubble tea drinks, Roasted Milk Tea with Red Bean and Mango Green Tea with Rainbow Jelly, were available on flights operated by Malaysian AirAsia with the airline code AK to 48 destinations, which include India, Hong Kong, Thailand and the Philippines.<ref name=dailyexpress-airasia>{{cite news|title=AirAsia upbeat on its F&B growth|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=82028|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Daily Express|date=6 July 2012}}</ref> The collaboration was organised by Chatime Malaysia's CEO, Bryan Loo.<ref name=dailyexpress-airasia/>\n\nChatime became the first beverage company in Malaysia to host an official account on [[WeChat]]. To mark the collaboration, Chatime gave away 1 million cups of drinks worth over  [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]6 million/[[United states dollar|US$]]2 million through digital coupons made available via the WeChat platform.<ref name=wechat-bp>{{cite news|title=WeChat and Chatime offer 1 million cups of Chatime |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/10/21/wechat-and-chatime-offer1-million-cups-of-chatime/|accessdate=30 December 2013|newspaper=Borneo Post|date=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nOther collaborations include partnerships with [[McDonald's]],  [[Horlicks]] from [[GlaxoSmithKline]],<ref name=mm-horlicks>{{cite news|title=The \"Why\" Behind the Chatime-Horlicks Alliance|url=http://marketingmagazine.com.my/index.php/categories/breaking-news/8812-the-qwhyq-behind-the-chatime-horlicks-alliance|accessdate=31 December 2013|newspaper=Marketing Magazine|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101023815/http://marketingmagazine.com.my/index.php/categories/breaking-news/8812-the-qwhyq-behind-the-chatime-horlicks-alliance|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  and biscuit brand Julie's.<ref name=bt-julies>{{cite news|title=Julie\u2019s teams up with Chatime|url=http://www.btimes.com.my/Current_News/BTIMES/articles/20131122005843/Article/|accessdate=31 December 2013|newspaper=Business Times|date=22 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101002340/http://www.btimes.com.my/Current_News/BTIMES/articles/20131122005843/Article/|archivedate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Brand ambassadors==\n[[File:Chatime outlet.jpg|thumbnail|right|A Chatime outlet in a shopping mall]]\n[[File:ChatimeOxford.jpg|thumb|right|A Chatime outlet]]\nChatime announced in 2012 that award-winning Taiwan actress [[Ariel Lin]] would serve as its [[brand ambassador]].<ref name=chatime-ariellin>{{cite web|title=Ariel Lin as the Official Brand Ambassador for Chatime|url=http://www.tea-time.com.tw/webe/html/news/show.php?num=6&kind=3&page=1|publisher=Chatime Press Release|accessdate=10 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231191247/http://www.tea-time.com.tw/webe/html/news/show.php?num=6&kind=3&page=1|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, the brand announced that [[Crystal Lee]] had become the lifestyle tea provider's first \"Chatime Friend\". The announcement was made soon after Lee became the youngest actress ever to have won the award for Best Actress at the 16th [[Shanghai International Film Festival]].<ref name=star-crystal>{{cite news|title=Award-winning child actress debuts in brand's programme|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/Business/SME/2013/07/02/Crystal-forges-special-friendship-Awardwinning-child-actress-debuts-in-brands-programme.aspx|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Counterfeit==\nIn South Korea, Chatime said it would take legal action against a store which sold similar products and was recruiting potential franchises.<ref name=wca-korea>{{cite news |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20121018000142&cid=1102 |title=Taiwanese bubble tea chain opens first outlet in South Korea |newspaper=[[WantChinaTimes]] |date=18 October 2012 |accessdate=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231223229/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20121018000142&cid=1102 |archivedate=31 December 2013 }}</ref> Additionally, in Malaysia, they will seek an injunction against  newly launched [[Tealive]] for operating and selling similar products and the possibility of using the same trade practices as its predecessor, Chatime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/03/16/chatime-malaysia-sues-tealive |title=Chatime Malaysia sues Tealive |date=16 March 2018 |website=The Sun Daily |publisher=Sun Media |accessdate=27 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316111512/http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/03/16/chatime-malaysia-sues-tealive |archivedate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Legal & regulatory matters==\nIn Malaysia, the master franchisee agreement was terminated on 5 January 2017 by La Kaffa International due to contractual dispute with its country master franchisee, Loob Holding. This legal dispute attracted the attention of local media and is currently in arbitration in Singapore. La Kaffa held a press conference in [[Kuala Lumpur]] announcing it would be taking over the Malaysian Chatime business operations and development with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/malaysia-s-chatime-outlets-to-be-replaced-with-local-brand-after-7577712 |title=Malaysia's Chatime outlets to be replaced with local brand after franchise dispute |last=Naidu |first=Sumisha |date=25 January 2017 |website=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |publisher=[[Mediacorp]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> This however appears to be largely incorrect with Loob Holding rebranding 161 out of 165 Chatime outlets to Tealive brand on 17 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2017/02/17/loob-holding-rebrands-chatime-as-tealive/ |title=Loob Holding rebrands Chatime as Tealive |date=17 February 2017 |website=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star Online]] |publisher=Star Media Group |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1317151/chatime-is-tealive-from-now-on-says-loob |title=Chatime is Tealive from now on, says Loob |date=17 February 2017 |website=[[Malay Mail]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Due to Loob Holding's alleged use of unapproved ingredients (which were later found out to be collaborations with other brands for localization purposes),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://says.com/my/news/la-kaffa-accuses-chatime-outlets-in-malaysia-of-using-unapproved-ingredients |title=La Kaffa Accuses Chatime Outlets In Malaysia Of Using \"Unapproved Ingredients\" |last=Balakrishnan |first=Nandini |date=3 February 2017 |website=[[Says Sdn Bhd|Says]] |publisher=[[Rev Asia]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> questionable practices, and a blatant breach of the terms of contract, La Kaffa International director Chen Zhao sought an injunction against the former master franchisee from operating a similar (bubble tea) business in Malaysia. On 29 May 2017, the High Court dismissed the injunction bid by La Kaffa International, against Loob Holding Sdn Bhd, from carrying a similar business as Chatime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/05/29/court-dismisses-chatimes-bid-for-injunction-against-ex-franchise-holder/ |title=Court dismisses Chatime's bid for injunction against ex-franchise holder |last=Ho |first=Kit Yen |date=29 May 2017 |website=[[Free Malaysia Today]] |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Judicial Commissioner Wong Kian Kheong, in his oral judgement, ruled that the injunction would cause great risk of injustice to Loob Holding and its business and also associates. The court also found that the franchise termination by La Kaffa was done in bad faith. While both companies have taken their dispute to the Singapore International Arbitration Centre, La Kaffa reportedly tries to persuade Loob Holding to settle this matter outside court.\n\nChatime Australia is alleged  to have underpaid 152 employees of 10 company-owned outlets across in Sydney and Melbourne a total of about $169,000.<ref name=\"9Newsunder\">{{cite news |last1=AAP |title=Chatime bubble tea chain allegedly underpaid staff |url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/chatime-australia-bubble-tea-chain-underpaying-staff/aa0c7f0c-1b68-4503-b26d-314852dbfdca |accessdate=28 December 2019 |agency=9News |date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bubble tea]]\n*[[Tea house]]\n*[[Tea culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chatime.com.tw/zh Official Taiwanese Website]\n*[http://www.chatime.com.tw/en Official English Website]\n\n[[Category:Tea houses]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese brands]]\n[[Category:Tea brands]]\n[[Category:Bubble tea brands]]\n[[Category:Tea companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Tea estates]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hsinchu]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Taiwan]]\n", "name_user": "203.220.226.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLocations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chatime"}
